<HEADLINE>
MOTC VICE MINISTER OFFERS TO RESIGN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Sept.  27  (CNA) (By Victor Lai)
</P>
<P>
Ho Cheng-tan, vice minister of the Ministry of Transportation and
Communications (MOTC), said Thursday that he has presented his
resignation to the ministry's chief, Yeh Chu-lan.
</P>
<P>
He cited "personal factors" as the reason for quitting.
</P>
<P>
Yeh confirmed to lawmakers at the Legislative Yuan that Ho was to
resign, but denied speculation about her "disharmony" with Ho, stating
that Ho has contributed much to the MOTC and she has been doing her
best to retain him.
</P>
<P>
According to Yeh, when Ho assumed the position of vice minister in May
last year, he expressed his hope to serve at the post for only one
year.
</P>
<P>
She said that Ho presented his resignation in August and she has been
trying to retain him because of his good performance in the government
team.
</P>
<P>
Ho is believed to have enjoyed the trust of President Chen Shui-bian.
He was chief of the Bureau of Transportation under the Taipei City
Government when Chen was Taipei mayor.
</P>
<P>
Ho has said that he wants to make contributions to society, but is
tired of political red tape.
</P>
